fels, Bayern, Duitsland"},"en":{"1209–1248":"1209–1248","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1214–1263":"1214–1263","1220–1279":"1220–1279","1230–1271":"1230–1271","1231–1272":"1231–1272","1180–1234":"1180–1234","1192–1231":"1192–1231","7 May 1231":"7 May 1231","7 May 1234":"7 May 1234","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1272":"1272","1271":"1271","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1209":"1209","21 June 1208":"21 June 1208","Besançon, Doubs, Franche-Comté, France":"Besançon, Doubs, Franche-Comté, France","Andechs, Starnberg, Oberbayern, Bavaria, Germany":"Andechs, Starnberg, Bavaria, Germany","Lichtenfels, Landkreis Lichtenfels, Bavaria (Bayern), Germany":"Lichtenfels, Lichtenfels, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Meran","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Luis, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Ramon, Ricardo, Alfredo, Javier, Julio, Raul.","Spanish (<b>Terán</b>): habitational name from Terán in Cantabria.","Slovenian: probably a nickname derived from <i>terati</i> ‘to push; to torture’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Otto","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a short form of any of the various Germanic compound personal names containing the element <i>od</i>, <i>ot</i> ‘prosperity, wealth’ (  compare the corresponding Old English <i>ēad</i> in names such as  Edward   and   Edwin  ).  St Otto of Bamberg  (  d. 1139 ) was a missionary to the Pomeranians.  Otto the Great  (  912–73 ) is generally regarded as the founder of the Holy Roman Empire, and the name has been borne by several members of German and Austrian royal houses. It was recorded occasionally among immigrants to England from the Low Countries in the 14th century, but failed to establish itself. Since the 19th century it has again been used occasionally in the English-speaking world, mostly among immigrants from Germanic countries."],"variants":[]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Ronald .  It is sometimes used as a given name in its own right."],"variants":[{"name":"Ronald","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (composed of <i>regin</i> ‘advice, decision’ (also, ‘the gods’) + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’). This name was regularly used in the Middle Ages in northern England and Scotland, where Scandinavian influence was strong. It is now widespread throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Duke Otto von Meran III was born in 1209, his father, Otto I Duke of Merania, was 29 and his mother, Beatrix von Hohenstaufen ,Erbin der Pfalzgrafschaft Burgund, was 17. He had at least 2 daughters. He died in 1248, at the age of 39, and was buried in Lichtenfels, Lichtenfels, Bavaria, Germany."},"et":{"1209–1248":"1209–1248","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1214–1263":"1214–1263","1220–1279":"1220–1279","1230–1271":"1230–1271","1231–1272":"1231–1272","1180–1234":"1180–1234","1192–1231":"1192–1231","7 May 1231":"7. mai 1231","7 May 1234":"7. mai 1234","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1272":"1272","1271":"1271","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1209":"1209","21 June 1208":"21. juuni 1208","Besançon, Doubs, Franche-Comté, France":"Besançon, Doubs, Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","Andechs, Starnberg, Oberbayern, Bavaria, Germany":"Andechs, Landkreis Starnberg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Lichtenfels, Landkreis Lichtenfels, Bavaria (Bayern), Germany":"Lichtenfels, Landkreis Lichtenfels, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1209–1248":"1209–1248","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1214–1263":"1214–1263","1220–1279":"1220–1279","1230–1271":"1230–1271","1231–1272":"1231–1272","1180–1234":"1180–1234